00:18:40.700 --> 00:18:44.710
and selling subscriptions.

00:18:44.710 --> 00:18:47.730
So how can Google help
you grow even more?

00:18:47.730 --> 00:18:50.490
Today, I'm going to cover
the new capabilities we built

00:18:50.490 --> 00:18:54.690
in the subscriptions platform to
help you reach new subscribers,

00:18:54.690 --> 00:18:57.150
as well as retain them.

00:18:57.150 --> 00:19:00.070
So let's start with reach first.

00:19:00.070 --> 00:19:03.450
Today, all subscriptions
are sold in-app.

00:19:03.450 --> 00:19:05.620
And you might think,
well, obviously,

00:19:05.620 --> 00:19:07.780
subscriptions are sold in-app.

00:19:07.780 --> 00:19:11.620
But consider this probably
very familiar situation.

00:19:11.620 --> 00:19:13.660
A user installs your app.

00:19:13.660 --> 00:19:15.700
They get to a paywall.

00:19:15.700 --> 00:19:18.200
They're like, I don't
know what this is.

00:19:18.200 --> 00:19:20.620
So then they uninstall your
app and post a one star review

00:19:20.620 --> 00:19:22.510
on your store listings page.

00:19:22.510 --> 00:19:25.120
And they've never
even tried your app.

00:19:25.120 --> 00:19:28.000
Or consider this other
familiar situation.

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:31.180
A user is using your app for
years using the free content,

00:19:31.180 --> 00:19:34.090
and they never even realize that
you had a subscription with all

00:19:34.090 --> 00:19:36.470
this amazing content behind it.

00:19:36.470 --> 00:19:39.100
And so what if we could help
you surface your subscription

00:19:39.100 --> 00:19:43.430
earlier, and maybe help the
user subscribe earlier, too?

00:19:43.430 --> 00:19:48.320
So I'm super excited to announce
today Subscribe and Install.

00:19:48.320 --> 00:19:51.710
This is a new feature to
help the user discover

00:19:51.710 --> 00:19:53.930
that your app has
a subscription,

00:19:53.930 --> 00:19:56.330
subscribe directly
from the Play Store,

00:19:56.330 --> 00:20:00.670
and then we will auto install
your app in the background.

00:20:00.670 --> 00:20:02.500
How does this work exactly?

00:20:02.500 --> 00:20:05.550
Well, you tell us which SKU
you would like to feature on

00:20:05.550 --> 00:20:07.470
your store listings page.

00:20:07.470 --> 00:20:10.080
We'll offer the SKU
and change the button

00:20:10.080 --> 00:20:11.730
where the user installs.

00:20:11.730 --> 00:20:14.940
If it's a free trial, we'll
say Free Trial and Install.

00:20:14.940 --> 00:20:16.710
And when the user
clicks the button,

00:20:16.710 --> 00:20:18.730
they'll be asked to
buy the subscription.

00:20:18.730 --> 00:20:20.510
And when that's
successful, then we

00:20:20.510 --> 00:20:23.153
will auto install the
app in the background.

00:20:23.153 --> 00:20:24.570
Now, as Stephen
mentioned earlier,

00:20:24.570 --> 00:20:28.390
this does require the
new Billing Library.

00:20:28.390 --> 00:20:30.580
We've been running an EAP
for Subscribe and Install

00:20:30.580 --> 00:20:33.460
for the last few months with
over a dozen developers,

00:20:33.460 --> 00:20:35.740
and we've seen some
amazing results.

00:20:35.740 --> 00:20:40.127
We've seen an average of 34%
increase in paid subscribers.

00:20:40.127 --> 00:20:41.710
And keep in mind
that this is actually

00:20:41.710 --> 00:20:45.010
after their free trial.

00:20:45.010 --> 00:20:49.540
In fact, photo editor app Pixart
tried Subscribe and Install,

00:20:49.540 --> 00:20:52.320
and they saw an increase in
both free trials, as well as

00:20:52.320 --> 00:20:55.490
free trial conversions.

00:20:55.490 --> 00:20:57.980
So speaking of free
trials, free trials,

00:20:57.980 --> 00:21:02.270
again, are a super common way
for you to acquire new users.

00:21:02.270 --> 00:21:04.580
Over 70% of new
subscriptions are actually

00:21:04.580 --> 00:21:06.470
coming from a free trial.

00:21:06.470 --> 00:21:09.470
But today, free trials are
kind of one size fits all.

00:21:09.470 --> 00:21:11.390
When you set up your
subscription SKU,

00:21:11.390 --> 00:21:14.810
either everybody on that SKU
gets a free trial, or nobody

00:21:14.810 --> 00:21:16.350
gets a free trial.

00:21:16.350 --> 00:21:18.500
But so what if you want
to be more targeted?

00:21:18.500 --> 00:21:21.590
For example, what if you want
to offer a free trial only

00:21:21.590 --> 00:21:25.370
to users who churned
six months ago?

00:21:25.370 --> 00:21:27.860
So I'm super excited to
announce promotion codes

00:21:27.860 --> 00:21:29.970
for subscriptions.

00:21:29.970 --> 00:21:31.460
In the Google Play
Console, you'll

00:21:31.460 --> 00:21:34.280
be able to generate
one-time promotion codes.

00:21:34.280 --> 00:21:35.880
It's super simple.

00:21:35.880 --> 00:21:38.360
You tell us how many
promotion codes you want,

00:21:38.360 --> 00:21:41.120
and we'll give you a
bunch of one-time codes

00:21:41.120 --> 00:21:44.500
and a CSV for you to distribute
to your users via email,

00:21:44.500 --> 00:21:46.670
via in-app purchase
or other channels

00:21:46.670 --> 00:21:48.810
that you can reach the user.

00:21:48.810 --> 00:21:52.100
And so how it works is if
the SKU doesn't have a trial,

00:21:52.100 --> 00:21:54.900
users with a promotion
code will get a trial.

00:21:54.900 --> 00:21:57.470
If the SKU already has a
trial, then those users

00:21:57.470 --> 00:22:00.390
will actually get an
extended free trial.

00:22:00.390 --> 00:22:03.740
So this is great for targeting
specific sets of users.

00:22:03.740 --> 00:22:05.960
Imagine if you can
send a promotion code

00:22:05.960 --> 00:22:08.660
to a user who just
abandoned your buy flow,

00:22:08.660 --> 00:22:11.420
or to a user who churned
after never having

00:22:11.420 --> 00:22:13.840
engaged in your most
primary feature in your app.

00:22:16.410 --> 00:22:19.980
So that was the new acquisition
tools within subscriptions.

00:22:19.980 --> 00:22:21.990
But once you acquire
subscribers, of course,

00:22:21.990 --> 00:22:23.480
you need to retain them.

00:22:23.480 --> 00:22:27.110
And so let's dive into the
new features within retention.

00:22:27.110 --> 00:22:28.910
Today, when a user
says I'm going

00:22:28.910 --> 00:22:32.030
to manage my subscription,
what they really mean is

00:22:32.030 --> 00:22:34.190
they're going to cancel
your subscription.

00:22:34.190 --> 00:22:36.110
And frankly, there's
not much else they

00:22:36.110 --> 00:22:39.770
can do once they get to
the subscription center.

00:22:39.770 --> 00:22:42.630
And as a result, some users
tell us when they're canceling,

00:22:42.630 --> 00:22:45.045
I'm just canceling
because I needed a break.

00:22:45.045 --> 00:22:46.670
Or I'm canceling
because I can't afford

00:22:46.670 --> 00:22:49.730
the subscription this month,
but I'll be back next month.

00:22:49.730 --> 00:22:50.570
Guess what?

00:22:50.570 --> 00:22:52.490
Some of those users
don't come back.

00:22:52.490 --> 00:22:55.120
Some of those users forget.

00:22:55.120 --> 00:22:58.150
And so I'm happy to announce
that now you can let your users

00:22:58.150 --> 00:23:00.920
pause their
subscription instead.

00:23:00.920 --> 00:23:03.440
When you enable Pause on
the Google Play Console,

00:23:03.440 --> 00:23:05.480
it will surface a
prompt in the cancel

00:23:05.480 --> 00:23:08.300
flow asking the user if
they would rather pause,

00:23:08.300 --> 00:23:10.550
instead of canceling
their subscription.

00:23:10.550 --> 00:23:13.880
Users can also pause directly
from the subscription center

00:23:13.880 --> 00:23:17.380
for up to three months on
a monthly subscription.

00:23:17.380 --> 00:23:20.410
This is a great way to
save on potential churners,

00:23:20.410 --> 00:23:22.990
especially for users who
are leaving temporarily.

00:23:25.800 --> 00:23:28.700
So let's dive into a
specific case study.

00:23:28.700 --> 00:23:32.480
Brazilian medical app PebMed
integrated with Pause,

00:23:32.480 --> 00:23:34.550
and they saw an
immediate voluntary churn

00:23:34.550 --> 00:23:38.960
reduction of 24% with very
little integration work.

00:23:38.960 --> 00:23:44.780
This is a great
result. Now because I

00:23:44.780 --> 00:23:46.820
have to deliver a
message from our lawyers,

00:23:46.820 --> 00:23:47.837
your mileage may vary.

00:23:47.837 --> 00:23:48.920
This is just a case study.

00:23:52.050 --> 00:23:55.280
So how do you know if Pause
is going to work for you?

00:23:55.280 --> 00:23:57.500
Well, last year, we
announced a cancel survey

00:23:57.500 --> 00:23:59.420
that we would show when
the user's canceling

00:23:59.420 --> 00:24:00.590
their subscription.

00:24:00.590 --> 00:24:03.605
But this was only
available via the API.

00:24:03.605 --> 00:24:05.480
And so that made it
difficult for many of you

00:24:05.480 --> 00:24:07.340
to be able to
aggregate those results

00:24:07.340 --> 00:24:10.820
and make sense of
the information.

00:24:10.820 --> 00:24:14.230
So now we've built new reporting
in the Google Play Console.

00:24:14.230 --> 00:24:16.930
You can access these reports
in the cancellation reporting

00:24:16.930 --> 00:24:18.550
section.

00:24:18.550 --> 00:24:22.050
You'll be able to see both
the aggregated fixed responses

00:24:22.050 --> 00:24:26.880
and to look at trends over
time, as well as download

00:24:26.880 --> 00:24:30.150
a CSV of the free form
responses users put

00:24:30.150 --> 00:24:32.410
in when they answered other.

00:24:32.410 --> 00:24:34.990
Both of these together should
give you actionable insights

00:24:34.990 --> 00:24:38.200
for why users are leaving and
how you can improve your app

00:24:38.200 --> 00:24:40.930
to keep them.

00:24:40.930 --> 00:24:43.720
In fact, language
exchange app Tandem

00:24:43.720 --> 00:24:47.560
used the cancellation survey
to identify and implement

00:24:47.560 --> 00:24:50.520
new pricing optimizations.

00:24:50.520 --> 00:24:53.880
Brain training app
NeuroNation found out that

00:24:53.880 --> 00:24:56.670
through the cancel survey,
that one third of their users

00:24:56.670 --> 00:24:59.028
were churning due to
cost related reasons.

00:24:59.028 --> 00:25:00.570
And as a result,
they're now thinking

00:25:00.570 --> 00:25:03.270
about new win-back strategies
using real time developer

00:25:03.270 --> 00:25:04.800
notifications.

00:25:04.800 --> 00:25:07.590
So I encourage you all,
please open your console

00:25:07.590 --> 00:25:09.510
and check out the new
cancellation reports.

00:25:09.510 --> 00:25:11.213
What you see might surprise you.

00:25:11.213 --> 00:25:12.630
Ultimately, it's
going to give you

00:25:12.630 --> 00:25:15.300
a better understanding
of who your users are

00:25:15.300 --> 00:25:17.880
and why they're leaving.

00:25:17.880 --> 00:25:20.340
So we've talked a lot
about voluntary churn.

00:25:20.340 --> 00:25:22.440
Let's talk involuntary now.

00:25:22.440 --> 00:25:24.420
So involuntary
churn is when a user

00:25:24.420 --> 00:25:25.980
churns due to payment issues.

00:25:25.980 --> 00:25:28.470
For example, your
credit card got stolen,

00:25:28.470 --> 00:25:31.530
or your carrier billing
has a low balance.

00:25:31.530 --> 00:25:33.270
This is a super
common reason why

00:25:33.270 --> 00:25:36.150
users churn from subscriptions,
and it absolutely

00:25:36.150 --> 00:25:40.260
can be addressed, sometimes
with even dramatic impact.

00:25:40.260 --> 00:25:43.080
So we currently offer a feature
called Grace Period, which you

00:25:43.080 --> 00:25:45.160
can set to three or seven days.

00:25:45.160 --> 00:25:47.310
And right after a
payment decline,

00:25:47.310 --> 00:25:50.190
you will give access
to the subscription

00:25:50.190 --> 00:25:53.230
to the user for three or seven
days while in the background,

00:25:53.230 --> 00:25:56.670
Google's retrying the
user's payment method.

00:25:56.670 --> 00:25:59.550
But why is Grace Period
only three or seven days?

00:25:59.550 --> 00:26:01.350
For a lot of you,
it might actually

00:26:01.350 --> 00:26:03.420
be worth it to give
the user a little bit

00:26:03.420 --> 00:26:05.970
more time in your
app in exchange

00:26:05.970 --> 00:26:10.830
for extending that retry window
we have to recover the payment.

00:26:10.830 --> 00:26:12.780
And so we've released
two new options

00:26:12.780 --> 00:26:16.200
for Grace Period,
14 and 30 days.

00:26:16.200 --> 00:26:19.140
Both of these will give
you a longer retry window,

00:26:19.140 --> 00:26:22.413
so that you can reduce
your involuntary churn.

00:26:22.413 --> 00:26:24.080
And the best thing
about this is there's

00:26:24.080 --> 00:26:26.240
no integration required.

00:26:26.240 --> 00:26:29.900
It's just checking a box.

00:26:29.900 --> 00:26:33.230
